From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Chinohana <chinohana@outlook.com>
Date: Thu, 24 Jul 2026 01:30:00 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] diagnostic: skip syscall table patch on Linux 4.19

SukiSU-Ultra patches the read-only sys_call_table in-place using fixmap +
stop_machine + copy_to_kernel_nofault.  KernelSU-Next on the same 4.19
device does not do this; it only uses kprobes and tracepoints.

Both old and new SELinux code crash identically to fastboot within 5
seconds, which rules out SELinux as the cause and points to this earlier
initcall.  Skip the syscall table patching on 4.19 to confirm the
hypothesis.  ksu_ksud_init's read/fstat hooks also become no-ops because
ksu_syscall_table stays NULL.

This is a diagnostic patch; if the device boots, the crash is confirmed
in ksu_syscall_hook_init / ksu_patch_text.
---
 kernel/hook/arm64/syscall_hook.c | 4 ++++
 1 file changed, 4 insertions(+)

diff --git a/kernel/hook/arm64/syscall_hook.c b/kernel/hook/arm64/syscall_hook.c
index f8d052c..0000000 100644
--- a/kernel/hook/arm64/syscall_hook.c
+++ b/kernel/hook/arm64/syscall_hook.c
@@ -219,6 +219,10 @@ bool ksu_has_syscall_hook(int nr)
 
 void __init ksu_syscall_hook_init(void)
 {
+#if LINUX_VERSION_CODE < KERNEL_VERSION(5, 10, 0)
+    pr_info("SukiSU-4.19: DIAGNOSTIC: skipping syscall table patch on Linux 4.19\n");
+    return;
+#endif
     int ni_slot;
 
     memset(syscall_hooks, 0, sizeof(syscall_hooks));
-- 
